<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="18">
body elongate, brilliant metallic, uniform green/blue coloration; and bifid tarsal claws. Also, antennae serrated from IV antennomere; pronotal margin slightly marginate; scutellum long, triangular, with round apex; legs long, with long tarsi, last tarsomere surpassing 
<normalizedToken originalValue="½">1/2</normalizedToken>
the lobes of tarsomere III.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Southern Brazil, Argentina and Paraguay. Only two subspecies of this genus have been cited in Argentina.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
